# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1894-baltimore-orioles-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The **1878 Boston Red Caps season** was the eighth season of the franchise.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps won their second straight National League pennant.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1879-providence-grays-season] The **1879 Providence Grays** won the National League title in only their second season in the league.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1880 Chicago White Stockings season** was the ninth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fifth in the National League and the third at Lakefront Park.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 67–17.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1881 Chicago White Stockings season** was the tenth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the sixth in the National League and the fourth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 56–28.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1882-baltimore-orioles-season] The 19th century's version of the **Baltimore Orioles** were founded in 1882 as part of the new American Association.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1882-baltimore-orioles-season] Owned by wealthy Harry Von der Horst, the Orioles finished the season in last place with only 19 wins.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1894-baltimore-orioles-season] The **Baltimore Orioles** won their first National League pennant in 1894.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1894-baltimore-orioles-season] After the regular season's conclusion, the Orioles participated in the first Temple Cup competition against the second-place New York Giants.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1894-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles lost to the Giants in a sweep, four games to none.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1894-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles roster contained six future Hall of Famers: Wilbert Robinson, John McGraw, Dan Brouthers, Hughie Jennings, Wee Willie Keeler and Joe Kelley.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1894-baltimore-orioles-season] Every man in their starting line-up hit .300 for the season.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1894-baltimore-orioles-season] They bunted, hit-and-ran, Baltimore chopped, backed up throws, cut off throws, and had pitchers cover first.
[src:1894-baltimore-orioles-season/1894-baltimore-orioles-season] They also deadened balls by icing them, tilted baselines so bunts would roll fair, and put soap around the mound so an opposing pitcher would get slippery fingers if he tried to dry his hands in the dirt.
